'''Single table inheritance''' is a way to emulate [[object-oriented]] [[inheritance (computer science)|inheritance]] in a [[relational database]]. When [[Map (mathematics)|mapping]] from a [[database]] table to an object in an [[object-oriented language]], a field in the database identifies what class in the [[hierarchy]] the object belongs to.<ref>Martin Fowler ''Patterns of Enterprise Application Architecture'' (2003), p. 278</ref> All fields of all the classes are stored in the same table, hence the name "Single Table Inheritance". In [[Ruby on Rails]] the field in the table called 'type' identifies the name of the [[class (computer science)|class]]. In [[Hibernate (Java)]] and [[Entity Framework]] this pattern is called Table-Per-Class-Hierarchy and Table-Per-Hierarchy (TPH) respectively.,<ref>[http://www.asp.net/mvc/overview/getting-started/getting-started-with-ef-using-mvc/implementing-inheritance-with-the-entity-framework-in-an-asp-net-mvc-application]. ''Implementing Inheritance with the Entity Framework 6 in an ASP.NET MVC 5 Application (11 of 12)'', Retrieved November 3, 2015</ref><ref>[https://docs.jboss.org/hibernate/orm/3.5/reference/en/html/inheritance.html], ''Hibernate ORM documentation (5.0), Chapter 9. Inheritance mapping'', Retrieved November 3, 2015</ref> and the column containing the class name is called the Discriminator column.
